{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"658fdfb7-5533-4924-9aeb-4683bf992211","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is a managed code bug — it means your code is dereferencing a `null` reference at runtime. This is **not a CLR activation issue**.\n\n**CLR activation logs** diagnose problems like the wrong runtime being loaded, missing runtimes, or .NET Framework version conflicts. They won't help here.\n\nTo find your bug, you should:\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you the exact line where the `null` dereference occurs.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception debugging** — run under a debugger and break on `System.NullReferenceException`.\n3. **Review startup/initialization code** — look for uninitialized fields, missing DI registrations, or race conditions.\n\nDo you have the exception stack trace? I can help analyze it if you share it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84a92bdc-1184-4fc2-9410-f9bf8f6d2bc2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mention CLR activation logs specifically. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, the user's issue is a NullReferenceException after startup, which is a managed code exception — not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs help with things like:\n- The shim picking the wrong runtime\n\n\n- Failing to load any runtime\n- Unexpected .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n- Loading both v2 and v4 into the same process\n\nA NullReferenceException is a runtime bug in the application code itself, not a CLR activation problem. CLR activation logs won't help diagnose this. I should explain to the user why this skill isn't the right fit for their issue rather than using it.","outputTokens